# Thai Visa Company Content Writing Standard

Every article should be written for:

- Google
- ChatGPT
- Claude
- Gemini
- Perplexity

Assume individual sections may be quoted independently.

## Recommended structure

Whenever appropriate include:

1. Quick Answer
2. In Short Summary
3. Requirements
4. Eligibility
5. Costs
6. Timeline
7. Common Mistakes
8. FAQ
9. Related Resources
10. Next Steps

End reader-action process sections with a supported implementation step (see [`editorial-conversion-philosophy.mdc`](./editorial-conversion-philosophy.mdc)). CTAs should be consultative, not promotional.

Answer questions early.

Do not hide answers behind long introductions.

## Voice and style

Use:

- plain English
- short sentences
- examples
- practical explanations

Avoid:

- legal jargon
- government language
- immigration bureaucracy language
- marketing fluff
- em dashes (`—`) in user-facing copy (see [`punctuation.mdc`](./punctuation.mdc))

Write like an experienced visa specialist helping someone understand their options.

The reader should feel:

**"Finally somebody explained this clearly."**

## AEO requirements

- direct definitions
- concise answers
- comparison tables
- checklists
- FAQ sections

Every article should remain useful even if Thai Visa Company did not exist.

## Images

After the article is written, run the visual storytelling review (`visual-storytelling-system.mdc`).

- Set `heroImage` in meta from `blogArticlePhotography`
- Select assets from `lib/media/editorial-asset-library.ts`; never use `visaPageOnly` assets
- Add `<ArticleImage />` only where it strengthens the section
- Do not repeat the hero image in the body
- Prefer comparison graphics (`ArticleComparison`) and process diagrams (`ProcessSteps`) over extra photography where they communicate faster

Full standards: [`visual-storytelling-system.mdc`](./visual-storytelling-system.mdc), [`visual-editorial-system.mdc`](./visual-editorial-system.mdc), [`editorial-image-policy.mdc`](./editorial-image-policy.mdc)
